Optional Chaining

Optional chaining (?.) is used to safely access nested object properties.

Prevents errors when intermediate values are null or undefined.

Returns undefined instead of throwing an error.

Useful when working with API responses or deeply nested data.

Async and Await

Async functions allow writing asynchronous code in a synchronous style.

An async function always returns a Promise.

Await pauses execution until the Promise resolves.

Await can only be used inside async functions.

Improves readability compared to .then() chaining.

useEffect Dependency Rules

If dependency array is not provided, useEffect runs after every render.

If dependency array is empty ([]), it runs only once after initial render.

If dependencies exist, it runs when any dependency value changes.

State variables should always be created at the top of the component.

Hooks should not be used inside loops, conditions, or nested functions.

Routing in React

Routing allows navigation between different components/pages.

React Router is commonly used for routing.

CreateBrowserRouter is used to define routing configuration.

Routing configuration specifies which component loads for each path.

RouterProvider and Outlet

RouterProvider provides routing configuration to the application.

Outlet is used to render child components inside a parent layout.

Helps implement nested routes.

Enables layout-based routing structure.

Client Side vs Server Side Routing
Client-side routing:

Navigation happens without page reload.

Everything runs in the browser.

Faster user experience.

Used in Single Page Applications (SPA).

Server-side routing:

Browser requests a new page from server on navigation.

Page reload occurs.

Slower compared to client-side routing.

Dynamic Routing (useParams)

Dynamic routing allows URLs with variable values.

useParams hook extracts route parameters from URL.

Useful for pages like product details or user profiles.

Example: /product/:id.

Adding Images in React
Ways to add images:

Import images using import statement.

Store images in public folder and reference using path.

Load images from external URLs.

Use images in CSS (background images).

Public folder method is useful for large or dynamic assets.
